What happened to the Anglo-Saxons and Vikings?

Anglo-Saxon history records that towards the end of the 8th century there were many raids made by Vikings. This was the beginning of an ongoing battle for control over Britain between the Anglo-Saxons, and the Vikings. King Alfred the Great was able to stop the Vikings from taking over Britain. He did this by agreeing to peace, and allowing some Vikings to settle in eastern England. This area was called Danelaw. Over time, subsequent kings of England slowly drove out the Vikings. In 954, the Anglo-Saxons defeated the Viking king Eric Bloodaxe. After that, the remaining Vikings agreed to be ruled by the king of England.
